{
    int x { 1 };
    foo(x); // ambiguous match with foo(int) and foo(const int&)

    return 0;
}Step 2) If no exact match is found, the compiler tries to find a match by applying numeric promotion to the argument(s). In lesson (10.1 -- Implicit type conversion), we covered how certain narrow integral and floating point types can be automatically promoted to wider types, such asintordouble. If, after numeric promotion, a match is found, the function call is resolved.For example:void foo(int)
{
}

void foo(double)
{
}

int main()
{
